    </div>

    <p>The three acids used in sour candy each contribute differently to the sensory experience. Citric acid (found naturally in citrus fruits) produces a bright, immediate sour hit that fades within 10-15 seconds — it is the most common sour coating ingredient. Malic acid (from apples) creates a smoother, longer-lasting sourness that builds gradually and lingers for 30-60 seconds. Tartaric acid (from grapes) delivers the sharpest, most intense pucker of the three. Most premium sour gummies blend citric and malic acid in varying ratios to create a sour curve that hits hard initially (citric) and then sustains the sensation through the chewing experience (malic).</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
