        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Citric Acid</h4>
        <p>The industry standard. Bright, immediate sour punch that fades in 10-15 seconds. Extracted from citrus fruits or produced by fermentation. pH 2.1 in concentrated solution. Used in 90% of sour candy coatings.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Malic Acid</h4>
        <p>The sustainer. Smooth, building sourness that lingers 30-60 seconds. Extracted from apples or synthesized. pH 2.4 in solution. Creates the "long finish" in premium sour candy. Often blended with citric acid.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="target" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Tartaric Acid</h4>
        <p>The intensifier. Sharp, concentrated pucker at pH 2.0. Found naturally in grapes and tamarind. Used sparingly for extreme sour products. Creates the "face-scrunching" effect in competition-level sour candy.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Fumaric Acid</h4>
        <p>The extreme option. Strongest sourness per gram of any food-grade acid. Very slow dissolving — creates prolonged intense sourness. Used in extreme sour candies like Toxic Waste. Less common in vegan/organic brands.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>Pectin and sour are a natural pairing in food chemistry. High-methoxyl pectin — the type used in most gummy candy — <strong>requires an acidic environment (pH 3.0-3.5) to form a gel</strong>. This means pectin-based sour gummies have an inherent advantage: the same citric acid that creates the sour taste also strengthens the gummy's structural integrity. Gelatin gummies, by contrast, are weakened by acid, which is why conventional sour gummies sometimes become mushy under their sour coating.</p>
      <cite>Thakur et al., Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition, 2024</cite>
    </div>

