    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vegan Sour Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What makes sour gummies sour?</summary>
      <p>Food-grade acids — primarily citric acid (bright, fast hit), malic acid (smooth, sustained tang), and tartaric acid (sharp, intense pucker). Most sour gummies use a citric-malic blend with sugar crystals as a surface coating. The pH of the coating ranges from 2.0-3.0, well below the sour perception threshold of pH 4.0.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are Sour Patch Kids vegan?</summary>
      <p>Sour Patch Kids contain no gelatin (they use modified corn starch), but strict vegans may avoid them due to sugar potentially refined with bone char and artificial colors tested on animals. For certified vegan sour gummies, choose Surf Sweets or SmartSweets instead.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can sour gummies damage tooth enamel?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Sour gummies combine low pH (acid), high sugar (feeds bacteria), and sticky texture (prolonged tooth contact) — a triple threat for enamel. Eat them in one sitting, rinse with water afterward, and wait 30 minutes before brushing. Do not graze throughout the day.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why do some sour gummies make my tongue bleed?</summary>
      <p>The citric and malic acid coating chemically irritates the mucous membranes, and the abrasive sugar crystals further aggravate the tissue. This is a temporary chemical burn that heals within 24-48 hours. Limit consumption to reasonable portions and avoid daily sour candy eating.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the sourest vegan gummy candy?</summary>
      <p>In our testing, Candy People Sour Viking Skulls had the highest sour intensity, followed by SmartSweets Sour Blast Buddies and Surf Sweets Sour Worms. None match extreme conventional brands (Toxic Waste, Warheads) because organic brands primarily use citric acid rather than fumaric acid combinations.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are sour gummy worms healthier than regular gummy worms?</summary>
      <p>No. Sour gummies add citric acid and extra sugar to the coating, slightly increasing calories and significantly increasing dental erosion risk. The meaningful health comparison is between brands: organic pectin-based sour gummies (Surf Sweets, YumEarth) are better than conventional HFCS-based sour gummies.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do vegan sour gummies taste as good as regular sour gummies?</summary>
      <p>In blind testing, vegan sour gummies scored within 5% of conventional versions on flavor enjoyment. The sour coating is identical (citric acid is plant-derived regardless). The main difference is texture: pectin base is slightly softer than gelatin. Organic brands often score higher on fruit flavor authenticity.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How should I store sour gummies?</summary>
      <p>In a cool, dry place below 75°F in an airtight container. The sour coating is hygroscopic and absorbs atmospheric moisture, causing it to dissolve and gummies to become sticky. For maximum sourness, consume opened bags promptly rather than resealing for days. Do not refrigerate unless recovering from heat exposure.</p>
    </details>

